Certainly! You can use the `replaceAll()` method from the `String` class in Java to replace all occurrences of a specific word in a given string. Below is a Java code snippet that demonstrates how to replace the word "thief" with "hero" in the provided sentence:

```java
public class ReplaceWord {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Original sentence
        String sentence = "The thief was caught as he tried to flee.";

        // Word to be replaced and the replacement word
        String wordToReplace = "thief";
        String replacementWord = "hero";

        // Replacing the word using replaceAll() method
        String modifiedSentence = sentence.replaceAll(wordToReplace, replacementWord);

        // Printing the modified sentence
        System.out.println(modifiedSentence);
    }
}
```

When you run this code, it will output:

```
The hero was caught as he tried to flee.
```

This code snippet creates a new string with all instances of "thief" replaced by "hero", maintaining the original sentence's structure while altering its meaning.
